I LOVE to begin my keynote by asking audience members to turn to each other and complete this sentence:
.
“Today, I’m an Awesome Human because…”
.
We are all brilliant at criticizing  ourselves. And yet the best way to flourish and grow is to acknowledge the good in yourself AND from that place of love and self-respect, improve and get better.
.
My amazing audience today blew me away with their joy and energy when they did this exercise.
.
And I share it with you because I want you to practice embracing the good in yourself every single day.
.
“Today, I’m an Awesome Human because…”

A young man came up to me after my keynote and told me he was burning out - but couldn’t quit his job.
.
He asked me what he could do since he couldn’t really change his life.
.
I told him he didn’t need to change his life. This idea that you either have to make dramatic changes or just be stuck feeling how you are is misguided.
.
I thought that way too after I burned our. I thought I needed to quit my life and go and meditate in Nepal for a year to feel better.
.
But I couldn’t. I had a company to run and a family and a mortgage and all kinds of other life responsibilities. Like you do, too.
.
What I discovered is that I could heal and recover and feel dramatically better by making small daily changes WITHIN my life.
.
I made a commitment to do 3 things every day to fuel myself (I had never done this!)
.
I began to take a daily walk. To spend a bit of time just sitting and being silent. And to paint, I gave myself permission to paint, something I had always wanted to do.
.
Some days, none of these felt good. But I stuck to them (and some days it was just a walk and a few minutes of sitting and a book instead of painting.)
.
But just the fact that I was doing something for me was huge fuel. I began to have a supportive relationship with myself, and it translated into so many other things, like better self-talk and compassion.
.
I told all this to this young man and I hope I was able to get into his heart - and that he begins to do something every day to fuel himself.
.
Because that is all it takes to create a more supportive relationship with yourself. To feel better. To break free from burnout. To life a more fulfilling, happier life 💛

Don’t wait until you feel that you’ve “earned it” to do something every day that brings you joy. Joy is your life fuel. It’s your right. You never have to earn it.
.
I waited until I was 40 to earn the right to paint. I finished it as indulgent and selfish until then, something I hadn’t earned the right to do just for joy.
.
Do I wish I had allowed myself to paint for joy earlier in life? Big yes!
.
But am I grateful that I finally broke through this stupid idea that doing something just for joy is indulgent? Bigger yes!
.
I share this and my art to encourage you to stop thinking that you need to earn your joy. Never. It’s part of being human. The only thing you need to do is make time to practice your joy!💛
Learning = self-care. And we forget to make time to learn new things just for the sake of learning. So here’s my suggestion for your week 💛

What’s the point of all our productivity and efficiency if we don’t feel connected, alive, valued?
.
I love getting stuff done. I love being efficient. But none of that matters for it’s own sake.
.
So yes, when I write emails, I don’t just get to the point. I pause to think about:
.
- What do I wish for this person? (A good day, some rest, something else?) - and I tell them this in my email.
.
- How do I want this email to make this person feel?
.
I think we need more warmth, all of us. And sometimes, it’s worth trading efficiency to create it💛
.
Would to know what you think!
ZERO studies show that self-criticism leads to self- improvements. I have a suggestion for what you should try instead 💛

I used to have a panic attack if I wasn’t “working” aka at my computer by 8am. So it’s a bit surreal to acknowledge that moving slowly in the mornings and not jumping into work ASAP has been one of the best things I’ve done for my work and how well I do it.
.
But it’s true. So many of the things I’ve done to improve my mental health after my burnout turned out to be the best investments into my work, my success, my creativity.
.
Moving slower. Having more time where I’m just marinating or being, not doing. Reading more fiction or books the fuel my soul (less anything that has to do with my field directly). Starting my days softer.
.
I’m a fuller, better, healthier being. But I am also better as a speaker and author.
.
I know your brain might be telling you that you can’t move slower or you don’t have the flexibility. And I do want to acknowledge that while running my own business is so hard, the flexibility is a gift.
.
BUT I also want to tell you that I have worked with thousands of Awesome Humans in all kinds of life and work circumstances and it is ALWAYS possible to carve out some time, to move a little slower, to allow yourself to be more, to not always be rushing and doing.
.
Yes to-do lists are long and everyone is busy. But part of that is our narrative and our collective belief that being busy is the only way - and that moving slower or having down time will mean we won’t be able to get all the things done.
.
This isn’t true. I can speak from my direct experience that I am so much more productive now, I do work that has way greater and better impact, I’m a better mom, wife, and friend.
.
No, making down time and moving slower aren’t the only reasons for this. But they are a big part of it because they allow me to connect to myself, to fuel myself so I have more to give.
.
You can’t give what you don’t have. Please time to move slower and fuel your being 💛

What words do you use to describe what you do everyday?

I find that so many of us use small words.

We finish stuff on our to-do list. We get groceries. We make dinner. We have Zoom calls. We write emails.

And the more we tell these small stories about our days the smaller we feel ourselves.

So many people tell me they feel their lives don’t have meaning or that they aren’t doing enough.

I think so much of that comes from the lens through which we see what it is that we do.

So my invitation to you is to not belittle your efforts.

Is it just a Zoom call or did you leave a legacy of compassion by really caring about the other person?

Is it just doing stuff or did you leave a legacy of creativity or progress today with what you did?

Is it just doing laundry or making dinner or did you leave a legacy of care and nourishment of your family today?

What would change if you used bigger words to describe what you do?

What would change if you thought about the kind of legacy your daily actions are creating — and how your actions are helping others in small and huge ways?

You leave a daily legacy every day.

Practice recognizing it and acknowledging it.💛

Surrender to your curiosity…
.
I’m taking this 4-day intensive only course  with Jean Houston, someone whose work and thinking and ideas have deeply impacted me.
.
And she said this phrase “surrender to curiosity” - and I almost jumped up.
.
I love that so much. And reflecting on it, it’s something I’ve often done and love to do. I love to learn, to explore new things, to follow the tiniest of threads of what might be pulling at me.
.
This year in particular I’ve been intentional about NOT dismissing any small thing that might catch my attention.
.
A concept in a book I’m reading. A word. Seeing a quote from an author I know nothing about. I’ve pulled in so many of these tiny threads and many led me to discover new teachers who have hugely influenced me, great new books, works of art, ideas…
.
The key to this curiosity surrender is to not worry about where your curiosity is going to lead you - which is hard for our super focused productivity-loving brains.
.
But it’s important to not restrict yourself, to give yourself permission to explore just because you’re curious.
.
I feel this is both a huge part of our self-care and self-growth. And I hope this encourages you to surrender to your curiosity in some way today 💛

However you feel, you can always choose to move forward and support yourself through it — but you can only do it if you first allow yourself to experience your feelings.

Believe me, I teach emotional fitness for a living but I did NOT practice this for most of my life.

I was afraid that if I allowed myself to feel a difficult emotion, I would just get stuck in it.

Sadness was one I feared a lot. I was so afraid to allow myself to feel sad.

But the truth is that it is only by allowing yourself to feel what you feel, even if it’s difficult, that you open up a path through it.

Emotions are strong. Resisting or denying them doesn’t actually work — as Carl Jung said: “That which you resist, persists.”

But when you allow yourself to feel, when you acknowledge what you feel, you literally give your brain permission to move through it.

Think of your brain like a small child who is upset. Does it work to ignore the small upset child? I’m a mom of an 18 year-old and from my experience, not at all.

But once you honor the child, once you say: “OK, I understand this is how you feel, tell me more,” the child calms down.

The child and your brain need you to acknowledge them first, before you can figure out how to move forward.

This is the power of Acceptance:
 
1. Acknowledging what is and how you feel, without judgement.
2. Choosing to move forward in a way that reduces your struggle (by asking: “What is 1 thing I could do to move forward with less struggle?”)💛

Change is hard for the human brain - and our brain always focuses on the negative parts of change. Why? Because change brings uncertainty and uncertainty causes fear, so the brain thinks about all the negative stuff trying to “protect” us from it.
.
So if you’re feeling anxious to return to work after the holidays, please recognize this - and realize that you can choose to handle this transition with less stress and anxiety.💛
You always have the choice to improve your daily experience (and how you feel). This question will help you do it!💛

This morning I paused my work and went to have tea with my parents. 

My parents live 10 minutes away and yes, I know how immensely lucky I am to have them so close.

(We moved to Boston 15 years ago to be near them and while I’ve never felt at home here - I hate the winters - I wouldn’t trade this for anything.)

When I was driving back home, I realized something:

Earlier in my life, I wouldn’t have gone over to their house during the week.

I would have told myself a story that this was work time and you don’t take a break for anything during work.

I prioritized getting things done and being efficient above all else.

And I missed out on so much living. 

And also, on love and a lot of loving.

I still love to get things done. I still work a lot. And I love my work, which brings me so much meaning.

But if I can (and sometimes I can’t!), I will pause the doing to do the living and the loving.

And no matter what your schedule is like or how full your to-do list or how flexible or inflexible your schedule, I encourage you to do this too.

Within what is possible. And it is always possible.

You can always find tiny ways to savor living.

Yes, even at the expense of efficiency. 

Because the point of work and life isn’t to get things done. It is to do things that bring you meaning and joy and help you to feel that you’re truly alive.

And when you do those things, they give you the fuel to do all the doing and accomplishing, with tons of efficiency!💛

I spent 15 years of my career thinking I was a servant leader because I was focused on my team. But I was wrong:

I was a frazzled, impatient, and often overwhelmed leader.

Not because I didn't mean well.

But because I ignored my own well-being and mindset.

If you want to serve others, you need to have energy, self-awareness, and clarity of mind. A desire to help simply isn't enough (I had so much of this!)

So please recognize that the only way to be a truly servant leader is to turn your attention within yourself first.💛

.
I love to paint after a trip because it’s a way I can capture and express my impressions and feelings about what I experienced.
.
This is the power of doing something creative: It’s a way to process and experience what you feel without putting it into words.
.

Here’s the simplest thing you can do feel more JOY:

Get REALLY excited about the smallest things you love💥

I LOVE good fruit. 

I grew up in St.Petersburg, Russia, where it was cold a lot and good fruit didn’t exist.

But I was actually born in Baku, a beautiful warm city on the shores of the Caspian Sea, where good fruit was like oxygen.

So good fruit is in my blood, you could say. And when I can find it, I go all in!

This photo is of me eating an amazing guava at a fruit market in Bogota a few weeks ago. We took a fruit market tour on my birthday there and I couldn’t think of a better present than to discover and EAT so many amazing fruits.

Don’t be small and quiet about what brings you joy. Don’t hold back on your embrace of it. Don’t worry about it running out.

Dive into it all the way! Fuel your being with this joyful experience and allow yourself to just be in the joy.

It can be the tiniest thing, but if you fully embrace your JOY of it, it will be a HUGE thing that fuels you with so much energy.

Joy is never frivolous - it’s your life fuel!💛

If there is one HUGE lesson I learned after I burned out, it was this:

I always thought only slackers practiced self-care (I had no idea what this was other than it wasn’t for a hard worker like me!)

But I was so wrong.

Well-being and hard work aren’t two opposite choices.

Well-being is a HUGE non-negotiable input into your ability to work hard in a SUSTAINABLE way.💛
Gratitude expands the surface area of your brain’s attention 💛

How could you make yourself proud today?
.
If you feel tired, you could make yourself proud by making time to rest.
.
If you’ve got a lot to do, you could make yourself proud by approaching your to-dos with a sense of enthusiasm and clarity vs. dread and complaining.
.
If you’re working on something challenging, you could make yourself proud by focusing on your purpose for doing it vs. indulging in self-doubt.
.
If you’re feeling down, you could make yourself proud by practicing gratitude or reaching out to connect to a friend.
.
If you’ve got a lot of awesome energy, you could make yourself proud by making progress on a project or doing something that helps someone else.
.
At the end of the day (pun intended!), what matters isn’t what others think of you. What matters is how you feel about you.
.
And every day you have a chance to make yourself proud. Not by someone else’s standards, but by your own.
.
So how could you make yourself proud today?💛

Challenge is constant in life, but struggle is optional.
.
I’ve had a really crappy few days. Lots of unexpected challenges. Before I would just allow it all to swallow me up - I used to believe that when life is tough, you struggle!.
.
But you don’t have to. Struggle is your inner experience of a challenge and you always always always can choose to do something small to reduce it.
.
How? By supporting yourself.
.
It begins with a question:
.
What is something I could do to struggle a little less?
.
- Can I see this situation differently?
- Can I talk to someone?
- What could I do that could help me feel grounded or calmer?
.
There is always a way you can support yourself to struggle less. But you have to choose to do it and ask the question.💛
.
Oh, I’m supporting myself with some good food and watching a good show and going to bed early 💛

I’ve been thinking about this a lot since the young woman asked me this question….
.
You see, I was her when I was younger. I thought if you wanted to achieve a lot and have a great life you needed to hustle and struggle and go go go non-stop.
.
And I did all that and achieved a lot - but I never enjoyed any of it, I was constantly overwhelmed and exhausted, and eventually I burned out.
.
Oh, and I was impatient and often snappy with people I loved, and prioritized work over them often - I hate this but it’s true.
.
Here’s the thing:
.
You have to work hard to achieve great things. No doubt about it.
.
But hard work doesn’t mean constant struggle, never resting, being harsh towards yourself.
.
Actually, it’s the very opposite:
.
If you want to work hard and achieve great things, you MUST rest, you must do things outside of work that fuel you, you must practice self-compassion.
.
Without doing those, you will struggle and eventually, run out of energy. And you won’t enjoy the fruits of your hard work.
.
This is what I told this young woman and the audience of 600 Awesome Humans who were listening.
.
This is what I wish I had heard when I was younger.
.
And this is the message I want to share with you - and if I can, with every single Awesome Human in the world 💛
This is one of the most important skills you need to learn to improve your emotional fitness - and how you feel!💛

This will either help you exhale or disappoint you:

It’s been a bumpy few months and this week I really just wanted to hide under the covers and wallow in all the things that are getting me down.

I teach gratitude for a living - so there is a part of me that feels like I’m letting you down when I tell you that I feel like this.

But perhaps this is the most important thing for me to tell you:

You can’t just be one way all the time.

And you can be grateful for your life and want to hide from it for a while.

You can love your work and not want to do it some days.

You can be someone who has a generally optimistic outlook and lose faith for a bit.

I used to be so strict with myself and tried to always appear like I thought I had to.

That was one of the things that caused me to burn out. I didn’t give myself any space to be human, to feel how I felt, to have days or months when I didn’t have to be the person I was trying to project.

You’re not a storyline. You’re a person. And that means there will be days when you don’t feel the way you usually do.

And sometimes you will change, in small or big ways. And then maybe you’ll evolve in some way that is unexpected, even to you.

I’m not saying this is easy, but let yourself. Don’t cause yourself more struggle by trying to stick to the person you think you’re supposed to be.💛

Gratitude isn’t about ignoring what’s wrong. It’s a skill that balances out your brain’s negativity bias so you don’t ignore what’s right.

Research shows that creating a grateful mindset improves your ability to positively adapt amidst challenges (which is my favorite definition of resilience), reduces stress, and helps you find more opportunities to move forward through uncertainty.💛

A reminder that the lens with which you choose to look at a situation impacts how you see it and how you feel.
.
Yes, there are tons of challenging and annoying and frustrating things in life, all the time. It’s not all happy joy joy.
.
But you can either increase the frustration you feel or reduce it and help yourself move through it to a more fueling feeling.
.
And the answer is always in the outlook you choose, the story you tell yourself about it, and your willingness to be grateful for what is good while some stuff is frustrating 💛
A short walk outside - especially in the morning - is one of the most beneficial things you can do for your mental, emotional, and physical health 💛

Getting un-tired is an activity that takes time, just like doing all the things that make you tired takes time.
.
This seems simple, yet often we treat our tiredness as a nuisance that should just go away!
.
I used to do this all the time and to be honest, even though I teach this stuff for a living, I still have to talk back to my brain when it yells at me for being “unproductive and lazy” on days when I’m recovering from being tired.
.
Like today. Today was a day like that and I had to do a lot of talking back to my brain.
.
So I’m sharing this as fuel for your talks back to your brain when it tries to tell you that you should just push through exhaustion.
.
The truth is that you can’t - not for a long time. And also, you shouldn’t have to. That is not living, that is not what you’re here to do.
.
And before you tell me you don’t have time to get un-tired, I will tell you that I know you do. You can do less social media and less news and less checking email and you’ll have found magic time to rest, chill, fuel yourself, and get in-tired.
.
Please do, please don’t push through or tough it out. 💛
A simple but powerful end-of-day ritual to help you feel more balanced and not think about work non-stop 💛

You can have a lazy day. Or a full on awesome productive day. Or a day where you’re savoring so much joy or one where you just want to hide under the covers.
.
All of those are fine! What matters is that you choose with intention how you will live through this day, what your lens will be, how you want to show up to it.
.
That’s what matters. Not making the most of each day (omg I used to try to do that and when I didn’t I would berate myself and it was all so exhausting…!) Not living each day like it was your last (I’ve always hated this advice - how realistic is that?)
.
But on purpose. Live each day by choosing how to live it - and realize that not choosing intentionally is also, a choice. 💛
Small acts of kindness remind us that we aren’t alone, fulfilling our core human need to belong. When we feel this way, we bring our full awesome capacity to our work and everyone around us!

This is my wish for every woman in the world: To love your being and to care deeply for all of the amazing selves within you 💛
.
You are and do so much. You’re a caretaker and nurturer, a doer and creator, a partner and leader, a friend and colleague, a dreamer, artist, chef, writer, healer… and so much more.
.
Make YOUR list. Acknowledge and embrace YOUR many selves.
.
And when your brain or the world dares to suggest that it’s selfish to take care of you, remember that you’re taking care of so many selves within you that give so much to others and this world.
.
I know there are so many structural problems in our world that make being a woman so damn difficult.
.
But what I want to teach every single woman is to break through our own stories that make it difficult to live and be and thrive.
.
So on this International Women’s Day and every single day, practice loving your being. Recognize you don’t ever need to earn your love.
.
And embrace all the different amazing selves within you with care and nourishment.
.
You have so much to give. But you can’t give what you don’t have. So your care of you is your beautiful life’s work 💛
.

I believe that every single human has something unique and awesome to contribute in their lifetime…
.
… but it isn’t fate or something that will just happen.
.
Figuring out what your unique gift is takes courage and trying things that may not work and inner strength to keep trying even when it seems easier to do something else.
.
But I think this is the only way to live a rewarding life, to feel fulfilled and deeply satisfied.
.
I spent so much of my life doing awesome things… that weren’t fully true to my unique gifts. And while on the outside I was successful, I didn’t feel fulfilled… I felt like something was constantly missing.
.
I feel that my burnout was in part caused by this - by my pursuit of something that wasn’t aligned with my unique purpose.
.
When I leaned into what felt true to me - writing, teaching, speaking - everything shifted.
.
It’s never easy. There are many challenges. But I feel so fulfilled and rewarded and that’s amazing fuel to help me through the challenges.
.
Please dare to discover your unique gift and share it. It’s why you are here and we need your awesomeness!💛

I was hesitating posting this but then I wouldn’t be real with you…
.
I’ve been going through a lot and today has been a really difficult day. And while I did do an awesome keynote and was proud of every minute of it… it was a blip of joy amidst so much hard stuff.
.
A few weeks ago my leg began to hurt and eventually we found 2 tiny blood clots, one of them harmless but another on a deep vein.
.
It was scary and overwhelming but I have an amazing doctor and I’m in awesome hands being treated. (We think it’s from all my flying and not moving around a lot - I do now and water!! and always compression socks!)
.
I exhaled for a bit… before running into a bunch of things I didn’t expect on blood thinners (plus the stress of fly / don’t fly / will this happen again / I fly for a living!).
.
It’s been a LOT.
.
Then, after I got off the stage and back to my room, I found out the bank that holds my company’s money had failed… and some of that money that I work so hard to make is now at risk.
.
And then my kiddo my heart my bff got some disappointing news about a summer job she had really wanted…
.
After weeks of stress, all this made me want to break and I just wanted to be victim and wallow in “why is this happening to me!!!”
.
And you know, that’s Ok. It’s human… but I didn’t want to stay there.
.
So, I threw myself into Acceptance.
.
And reminding myself that it’s BOTH about fully accepting how I feel and the facts of the so many challenges that are here AND asking the most important question:
.
Given how things are and how I feel, what is 1 thing I could I do to move forward with less struggle?
.
My brain didn’t want to do this. It wanted to stay in the valley of struggle. But I did it anyway.
.
I couldn’t fix anything… but I could reach out for support.
.
So I texted my husband @avispiv and I called my docs and I called our former CFO just to hear his reassuring voice and talked to my amazing kiddo on the phone to hear she is OK.
.
You know what? It’s all still a mess but I don’t feel alone.
.
And I have new insight on how important that is. To not feel alone amidst the hard of life.
.
I’m grateful to not be alone - including being able to share with you 💛

No one wants your (non-existent) perfect…
.
… what we all want and seek in life and from each other is truth, beauty, and love, in all different forms.
.
Your authenticity and truth, your inner beauty, your compassion, care and other forms of love - those are your greatest gifts.
.
Share them generously!
.
In my previous post I shared some of the hard stuff I’m going through and how I’m feeling… and I’ve been completely overwhelmed with the generosity of love and support in the comments.
.
As I was thinking about why my post resonated so much, I kept coming back to this:
.
It was because I express truth and the beauty of the challenges and strength and fragility of human experience.
.

Have you ever thought: “As long as my child/partner/parent is happy, I’m happy,” or “As long as my work helps others, I’ll be happy”?

We become convinced that if people we deeply love and care about are happy, we’ll be happy too.

If we love our work and it has a positive impact on others, we’ll be happy and deeply satisfied.

But that isn’t true. 

And I say this with love: If you believe it’s true, it’s a lie you’re telling yourself.

I told myself this lie, too. As a mama (to a now 19 year-old amazing daughter!) I thought that if I gave her my all and she was happy, then I would be happy too.

Actually, let me be more honest:

I thought that I *should* be happy if she was happy.

So I used this as an excuse to ignore myself, my wellbeing, and my happiness for most of her life.

I did the same with my work.

I cared so much about our mission at Happier and I told myself that as long as we help a lot of people, I’ll be happy.

So many people who love their work, who are purpose-driven in what they do, think the same way… and like I did, often end up burning out.

Here’s the BIG TRUTH:

No one else’s happiness can make you truly, genuinely happy. You are not other people.

No amount of doing work that you love and care about can make you genuinely happy. You are not your work.

To be truly, deeply, genuinely happier, to live a fulfilling life that fuels you rather than drains you, you need to honor yourself as a human being, nourish all the different parts of yourself, and fuel your own joy and meaning.

Of course it matters if people you love are OK!

Of course it matters if your work is meaningful!

And both of these can significantly contribute to your happiness and sense of meaning in life.

But on their own, they will never be enough.

Honor yourself as a human being. Nourish all of the different aspects of yourself. Take care of your well-being and joy. 

And not only will you live a truly thriving, happier life, but you will also have so much more to give to the people and work you love and care about. 💛

Your car needs gas or electricity to do it’s job of being a car.

You need emotional, mental, and physical energy to do your job of being human.
.
It’s never “selfish” to go fill up your car - it needs fuel! And in the same way, it’s never “selfish” to practice self-care - you need fuel!

You work doesn’t need to be your life’s purpose. But if your work is not aligned with your natural gifts or things you care about, it negatively affects your well-being and can lead to burnout.

I learned this the painful way: by burning out.

I didn’t know this for the 15 years when I worked in tech and finance, as an investor, entrepreneur, product and UX leader.

My work was interesting (most of the time) and engaging. I cared about doing an awesome job and creating something meaningful.

But I always had this sense that I wasn’t “home”, like I wasn’t quite doing what some deep part of me wanted to do.

I had no idea what that was and this wasn’t a conscious thought, but deep inside I felt like I wasn’t a great tech product person or CEO.

The thing is, my inner critic took over and told me that I wasn’t good at my job. But in retrospect I think it was something way deeper in me trying to get me to be more honest about what my gifts were and how I could best share them.

I didn’t burn out just because I was doing work that wasn’t aligned with my gifts or what moved my soul, but it was a huge contributor.

And it took my burnout to stop me in my tracks and give me space - force me into it! - to think about what I had to give and how I could best give it to benefit others.

It wasn’t easy, it wasn’t linear, it was like an abstract painting that took many colors and strokes and changed and shifts.

I work very hard as a speaker, author, and entrepreneur now. Maybe harder than before. But because I do feels so aligned, I have a lot more energy and capacity to do my work.

It’s like when you align your work with your natural gifts and what you care about, you unlock this whole huge reserve of energy and ability to overcome challenges.

I share all this to encourage you to consider if what you do for work is aligned with what your gifts - you have many! - and what you care about.

It doesn’t have to align 100 percent. Rarely that’s possible. And if you feel the answer is no, you don’t need to quit tomorrow.

You can consider if there’s a way to shift your current work, to add more of what brings out your enthusiasm. You can take small steps. Each one matters.💛

Uncertainty is the hardest thing for the human brain to handle. Here are a few science-backed strategies to avoid getting stuck in the worry loop 💛

If you want to be happier, make things with your hands.

Making things with your hands is one the most essential contributors to your mental health and well-beating…

… and yet we don’t talk about it or practice it nearly enough.

When you make something tangible with your hands, your brain derives a deep sense of satisfaction. 

Making things with our hands has always been necessary for our survival so our brain rewards making.

Making something brings you into the moment and your direct experience, so it’s also a form of mindfulness, which fuels your mental health and reduces stress.

We are meant to make things with our hands and yet our modern lives, especially for knowledge workers, are often devoid of this kind of making.

We order food instead of making it. We type instead of writing by hand. We spend so many hours in our heads and in the digital world.

Could this lack of making be contributing to our increasing stress? Absolutely.

So make making a regular practice!

You don’t have to make art (I do and this photo is my first attempt at a 3-D foam painting - it was so fun to try something new and I love it!🎨)

Cooking, gardening, coloring, knitting, doodling are forms of making.

Folding the laundry and making the bed are forks of making if you bring your attention to doing them and think of them as making vs annoying chores.

Making a cup of coffee vs. using instant coffee is a form of making.

There are so many ways to make something in your day. And when you do, it’s a huge investment in your mental health, self-efficacy, and thriving.💛

How could you make your tomorrow self proud with what you do today?

This is a really awesome question to ask yourself.

Why? Because your tomorrow self can be a great guide for how to best approach your day and yourself today.

I wrote about this idea in my weekly email - link to sign up is in my profile! - and here are a few examples:

- If you feel tired today, you could make your tomorrow self proud by making time to rest -- this way, your tomorrow self will have energy to do what you want and need to do.

- If you’ve got a lot to do, you could make your tomorrow self proud by approaching your to-dos with a sense of enthusiasm and clarity vs. dread and complaining (this will help you get more done and avoid wasting unnecessary energy!)

- If you’re hesitating about getting your workout in, you could make your tomorrow self proud by getting to the gym or going for a walk or run outside.

At the end of the day (pun intended!), what matters isn’t what others think of you. What matters is how you feel about you.

So your tomorrow self can be a great motivator for choosing what you do and focus on today.

In fact, research shows that when we connect to our future selves, we make better choices.

The human brain likes short-term rewards -- which is why we reach for that extra cookie even though we've committed to healthier eating habits. The benefit of not eating the cookie is long-term but the benefit of eating it is right here and now (it tastes good!), so our brain convinces us to go for it.

This is where thinking about your future self can be so helpful. It changes your perspective and expands the timeline within which you see the impact of your actions. This is the research that inspired me to think about how I could make my tomorrow self proud.

I think it can be challenging for us to think too far ahead (a week seems long enough, right?!)

But connecting to my tomorrow self is something I can really grasp. It's tangible. I can get my mind around it and it gives me a more helpful lens for making decisions about what I do today.
.
So, how could you make your tomorrow self proud?💛

💛 My grandpa Misha taught me the most valuable lesson about happiness:

My grandpa would have been 99 years old today.

He left us 3 years ago but his spirit and his wisdom are with us always. 

He was a true awesome human, who never let challenges or difficulties alter his optimism, his love of life and his family, and his desire to be useful to others.

And oh, did he have challenges. He fought in and survived the war, took care of his family back in Russia where it wasn’t easy, and in his 60s, together with his wife, my grandma Mirra, and all of us, came to the US as a refugee — not speaking English, not knowing anything about this new life.

My grandpa is actually the one who gave us all hope and courage to leave the Soviet Union and try to come to the US as refugees. He was our guiding light.

A few years ago, my husband, daughter and I were visiting him in his little apartment that he had shared with my grandma Mirra, his wife for 67 years (!!!!) who passed away a few years before him.

We sat at their kitchen table and my grandpa was peeling oranges.

He was always peeling fruit and cutting it to give to us. Some of my fondest childhood memories are of my grandpa chasing me around to feed me fruit.

So we sat at the table and I told my grandpa that I wanted to interview him about happiness.

“What does it mean to you to be happy, dedulya?” I asked him.

He didn’t hesitate for a moment or take a pause from peeling oranges for us to eat.

“To be useful to someone else. That’s happiness. Every day, that’s what I try to do. When I am useful to someone, I am happy.”

This is one of my most cherished memories of my grandpa. 

And it’s the purest truth about what brings us the most lasting, meaningful, abundant happiness in life.

To be useful to someone else.

Thank you, dedulya, for your being, your love, and your wisdom. Today, in honor of your birthday, we will eat ice cream (which you loved!) and try to be useful to someone else.💛💛💛

This is the most powerful way I know how to get out of frustration and annoyance:
.
Imagine your life without the thing that’s causing your frustration. Really imagine it.
.
Annoyed at a delay at the airport? Imagine your life without being able to fly or having somewhere to fly to.
.
Frustrated with your significant other? Imagine living without them.
.
Frustrated at your boss? What would your life be like if you had to take care of all the things your boss does - or without this job?
.
When I do this it immediately takes the edge off.
.
The brain is amazing at focusing on what’s wrong. What’s annoying. It’s called the negativity bias.
.
But do you really want to live in negativity jail your brain puts you in?
.
Does that fuel you?
.
My answer is no.
.
And no I’m not suggesting you never address your frustrations  work out problems, or heck, allow yourself to feel frustrated and blow off some steam.
.
I’m writing this during a day of a lot of airline delays and changed flights and annoyance - I’m not going to pretend that I can feel good about it.

.
When I imagine my life without that it sucks. I don’t want that life. So yeah, this is annoying day of travel but I’m not in a frustration spiral because of it.
.
The next time you feel yourself well up with frustration, try to imagine your life without the thing that’s frustrating you. I think you well-being and mood will thank you 💛

Your inner atmosphere either fuels others with energy or drains it from them.

This may be a hard thing to get really honest about but it’s worth doing - without self-judgement.

I used to drain energy from people often. Sure, I also uplifted them a lot but when I was in inner turmoil, feeling overwhelmed, focusing on everything that was wrong including with myself, I drained energy from people - at work, teams I led, in my family.

But I couldn’t help it. The dark cloud I had inside I brought it to everyone around me - not all the time, but often.

We forget that we impact people not just with what we say or do but with our inner atmosphere.

Think of it like Earth’s athmosphere (a loose analogy):

When the clouds are dark and heavy, we often feel down or even sad.

When there is sunshine, it uplifts us.

I’m not suggesting that should be a constant ray of sunshine - or that you should ever force it, like by being fake positive (I tried this with my teams - everyone can sense it and it creates lack of trust because they feel your true inner atmosphere but you’re faking something else.)

But it is a fact that how you show up, what your inner atmosphere is like, has a very powerful impact on others.

So when you take care of yourself, when you take care of your inner atmosphere, when you do what brings you joy, what uplifts you, what fuels your being, you’re literally and directly positively impacting everyone around you.💛
Instead of dreading change, what if you could see it as an invitation to grow and imagine what’s possible?💛

I wrote this for myself — and of course for you — because my brain has been loudly yelling at me about all the things I should have done this year but I haven’t. UGH!

I think it’s because we’re nearing the end of the year and my inner critic sees a great opportunity for this “you haven’t done enough” - ness.

Is your brain yelling at you about all the things you should have done this year.. or this week?

If yes, let me tell you what to do when this happens:

Step 1: Recognize that your brain does not give you accurate thoughts. 

Your brain tells stories and they are filtered through many lenses: negativity bias, fear of not being good enough, pas patterns, etc.

Step 2: EDIT THE STORY!

You are the editor of your thoughts. This means you can take the thought your brain gives you and ask 2 things: Is it true and is it helpful?

True = it should have facts to support it. And these stories where the brain decides what you should or should not have done by now are not based on facts. Because who has the clipboard with when you’re supposed to do what? (Answer: no one.)

Helpful = it fuels you, it motivates you. I’ve never comes across a thought that told me I haven’t done that was helpful.

Step 3: Tell a better story.

This is where you shift! Instead of “I should have done this and that by now…” how about: 

“I want to do X so I’m going to take this step right now towards it.”

Step 4: TAKE THAT STEP!

This shift from self-criticism into action is so powerful.

Your brain loves a sense of progress and as soon as you take this action step, it will stop with the unhelpful useless stories and focus on coming up with more and more steps.

I did these steps today and I feel so much better!

I’d love to know if they resonate with you — tell me in the comments!💛💥

Change requires forward energy. But if you’re spending all your energy looking back, you won’t have enough.⤵️

It can be tempting to keep retelling stories that led you to be where you are.

To analyze and think through and overanalyze all the reasons why you are how you are and feel what you feel.

And reflection and learning from your path are essential...

... but not if they swallow up all of your energy and attention.

Change requires forward energy.

If you want to change something in yourself or your life, practice the 2 steps of acceptance:

1. Acknowledge how things are and how you feel — do this with clarity, focusing on the facts, instead of judgement, which is your story about the facts.

2. From that place of clarity, what is 1 thing you could do to move forward to where you want to be? Do that thing. What is the next? Do that thing.

You won’t get to a new place where you want to be by constantly analyzing how you got to where you are today.

Accept that this is how it is. And use your energy and capacity to take steps to move forward in ways that feel true and aligned to you and where you want to go.💛
